od, when England became a desirable Occidental space, connected with but superior to distant lands. Delving into the works of Wordsworth, Austen, Byron, Dickens, and others to trace an arc of celebration, ambivalence, and criticism influenced by these imperial dynamics, Makdisi demonstrates the extent to which Romanticism offered both hopes for and warnings against future developments in Occidentalism. Revealing that Romanticism provided a way to resist imperial logic about improvement and moral virtue, Making England Western is an exciting contribution to the study of both British literature and colonialism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCivilization, Western. 0aImperialism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  arace, racism, racist, imperial, imperialism, imperialist, culture, cultural, occidental, occidentalism, orientalism, colonialism, colonist, colonizers, colonial, colonizing, english, britain, united kingdom, travel, foreign relations, western, ethnic, ethnicity, romantic, wordsworth, byron, dickens, literary, literature, criticism, critique.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022692313040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226923154423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226923154/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles